00:20:58,880 --> 00:21:08,959
So, first, if you look at the description of Dido's death, it is said that it's neither fateful nor is it merited, and it is untimely.

182
00:21:09,279 --> 00:21:19,039
So, if you remember, the underworld's not really ready for her, that's why her soul can't leave her body, and we have to send for Iris to come down and help her leave her body.

183
00:21:19,360 --> 00:21:23,439
And before she kills herself, she calls all of the gods for witnesses.

184
00:21:23,439 --> 00:21:31,680
And I think that's an interesting moment because she does not what the gods want, and she also does not do what fate has in store for her.

185
00:21:31,999 --> 00:21:39,040
And despite the fact that she neither does what the gods want, nor what her fate is, the gods don't condemn her.

186
00:21:39,040 --> 00:21:42,719
And she's warned by her sister, but she's never condemned.

187
00:21:43,039 --> 00:21:50,479
And then we have another encounter with Dido in the underworld, where Aeneas goes to the underworld and he meets with Dido.

188
00:21:50,799 --> 00:21:54,000
And what happens is that Dido doesn't even talk to him.

189
00:21:53,999 --> 00:21:58,079
She looks at him, but then she turns back and goes away.

190
00:21:58,080 --> 00:22:04,039
And Aeneas is full of pity and full of tears and says, Talk to me, this is the last time we'll see each other.

191
00:22:01,519 --> 00:22:07,560
And she doesn't want to talk with him.

192
00:22:07,719 --> 00:22:10,840
But he says, well, I've simply done what fate had me do.

193
00:22:10,840 --> 00:22:12,359
I had to do it.

194
00:22:12,360 --> 00:22:16,120
And in my interpretation, I think that her choice is much better.

195
00:22:16,120 --> 00:22:20,439
I think that she made the much more resolute and interesting choice and sticks with it.

196
00:22:20,439 --> 00:22:23,640
And that's what I'm going to talk about next.

197
00:22:23,640 --> 00:22:27,640
I think that it's not Aeneas who's great in the scene, but it's really Dido.

198
00:22:27,959 --> 00:22:32,439
And I also don't suppose that we are to feel pity for Dido.

199
00:22:32,439 --> 00:22:34,279
I think that she's not to be pitied.

200
00:22:34,279 --> 00:22:43,319
Okay, in concluding, I think that Virgil's Aeneas is as a work as a work of art because it does unify the Roman way of life.

201
00:22:43,320 --> 00:22:48,039
And this can be also shown in its popularity and its authority.

202
00:22:48,680 --> 00:22:57,799
It is a work of art because it's self-referential and autopoetic in the sense that it does create the emotion that it presupposes as a core value.

203
00:22:57,799 --> 00:23:12,039
And then in this sense, if you remember that I talked about the myths of the failed authorship, I think that this is more than just an anecdotal embellishment because it really becomes a work with which the culture itself is creating.

204
00:23:13,320 --> 00:23:27,479
And for the new reading that I'm giving of Dido, it's not essential whether Virgil intended for this or not, but it's essential that these elements can be present or can be thought of present in the way of being.

205
00:23:27,799 --> 00:23:28,199
T.S.

206
00:23:28,199 --> 00:23:36,359
Eliot once described the meeting of Dido and Aeneas in the underworld, as the most civilized moment in Western literature.

207
00:23:36,360 --> 00:23:41,959
